5000|$|<b>Barkcloth</b> or bark cloth is a {{versatile}} material {{that was once}} common in Asia, Africa, Indonesia, and the Pacific. <b>Barkcloth</b> comes primarily from trees of the Moraceae family, including Broussonetia papyrifera, Artocarpus altilis, and Ficus natalensis. It is made by beating sodden strips of the fibrous inner bark of these trees into sheets, which are then finished {{into a variety of}} items. Many texts that mention [...] "paper" [...] clothing are actually referring to barkcloth.Barkcloth has been manufactured in Uganda for centuries and is Uganda's sole representative on the UNESCO Intangible Cultural Heritage Lists.|$|E
50|$|<b>Barkcloth</b> has an {{affinity}} with the semi-abstract designs of some primitive peoples, in which mans own products are rendered into their simplest forms and incorporated as {{elements in a}} geometrical design.|$|E
